'''Ivan Simon Cary Elwes''' (born 26 October 1962), known professionally as '''Cary Elwes''', is an English actor, known for his performances in films such as ''[[Lady Jane (film)|Lady Jane]]'', ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'', ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]'', ''[[Hot Shots!]]'', ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'', ''[[Liar Liar]]'', ''[[Saw (film)|Saw]]'' and ''[[Saw 3D]]'', ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'', and ''[[Kiss the Girls (film)|Kiss the Girls]]''.

==Personal life==
Elwes was born in [[Westminster]], London, and is the third and youngest son of portrait-painter [[Dominick Elwes]]&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.filmreference.com/film/37/Cary-Elwes.html Cary Elwes Biography (1962–)]&lt;/ref&gt; and interior designer [[Tessa Kennedy|Tessa Georgina Kennedy]], who is of [[Croats|Croatian]] and [[Anglo-Irish]] descent. His paternal grandfather is painter [[Simon Elwes]], whose father was the diplomat and [[tenor]] [[Gervase Elwes]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/b/a/t/Robert-A-Battle/BOOK-0001/0000-0001.html Family Tree Maker's Genealogy Site: User Home Page Book: Cary Elwes: Title Page]&lt;/ref&gt; His brothers are [[Damian Elwes]], an artist, and [[Cassian Elwes]], a producer and agent. He is the stepson of [[Elliott Kastner]], an American film producer. He was raised Roman Catholic.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2005/12/04/2005-12-04_the_spirit_moved_him.html|title=The spirit moved him|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|quote =Elwes, who grew up a Catholic,...|date=4 December 2005|accessdate=13 September 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Elwes attended [[Harrow School]] in London and [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[Bronxville, New York]], where he studied, among other acting-related subjects, [[German Expressionism|German Expressionist Film]]. While living in New York, Elwes studied acting at both the [[Actors' Studio]] and the [[Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

In 1991, Elwes met photographer [[Lisa Marie Kurbikoff]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} They became engaged in 1997 and wed in 2000.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} The couple have one daughter.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

One of his ancestors is [[John Elwes (politician)|John Elwes]], who is believed to be the inspiration for [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] in [[Charles Dickens]]' ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' (1843).&lt;ref&gt;[http://thecia.com.au/reviews/c/images/christmas-carol-production-notes.doc ''Disney's A Christmas Carol'' press notes], p. 6 (PDF). [http://www.webcitation.org/5tLrhTKfT WebCitation archive]. [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:uqqAzKJa3jUJ:thecia.com.au/reviews/c/images/christmas-carol-production-notes.doc HTML version]. &quot;Elwes has a unique connection to the story. The actor is actually related to the man believed to be the inspiration for Scrooge. 'John Elwes is an ancestor of mine who was a renowned miser,' says Elwes. 'He was a politician who changed his name from Meggot to Elwes in order to gain favour with his uncle, Sir Harvey Elwes, who he knew was going to die without an heir and he had tons of money. And it worked. He managed to get all Mr. Harvey Elwes' estates and proceeded to become one of the most famous misers in English history. He was renowned for never changing his clothes.{{'&quot;}}&lt;/ref&gt; Elwes played the role of Dick Wilkins in the [[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|2009 film adaptation]] of the novel.

==Career==
===Film===
Elwes made his acting debut in [[Marek Kanievska]]'s film ''[[Another Country (1984 film)|Another Country]]'' (where he played James Harcourt, a young and sentimental homosexual student from an English [[boarding school]]), with [[Rupert Everett]] and [[Colin Firth]]. The film, adapted from a play, was loosely based on the formative years of British spy [[Guy Burgess]], one of the [[Cambridge Five]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} He went on to play [[Guilford Dudley]] in the British film ''[[Lady Jane (film)|Lady Jane]]'', costarring [[Helena Bonham Carter]]. His performance in that film led director [[Rob Reiner]] to cast Elwes in another leading role, this time as the stable boy turned swashbuckler Westley in the comedy ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''.
[[File:Cary Elwes Saw 3D premiere cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Elwes attending the ''[[Saw 3D]]'' premiere on October 27, 2010.]]
He continued working steadily, varying between dramatic roles, as in ''[[The Bride (film)|The Bride]]'' (1985) with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] and [[Jennifer Beals]], to the [[Academy Award]]-winning ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), and comedic roles, as in ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' (1991). In 1993, he starred as [[Robin Hood]] in [[Mel Brooks]]' comedy, ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]'' Elwes also appeared in such films as [[Francis Coppola]]'s adaptation of ''[[Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'', ''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]'', ''[[Rudyard Kipling's The Jungle Book]]'', ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'', ''[[Liar Liar]]'', ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]'', ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' and ''[[Kiss the Girls (film)|Kiss the Girls]]''. In 2004, he starred in the [[Horror film|horror]]/[[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] ''[[Saw (film)|Saw]]'' which, at a budget of a little over $1 million,{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} grossed over $100 million worldwide.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} The same year he appeared in ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]'', portraying the villain rather than the hero. He made an uncredited appearance as Sam Green, the man who introduced [[Andy Warhol]] to [[Edie Sedgwick]], in the 2006 film ''[[Factory Girl]]''. In 2007, he appeared in [[Garry Marshall]]'s ''[[Georgia Rule]]'' with [[Jane Fonda]]. In 2009 Elwes worked on two [[performance capture]] films, [[Robert Zemeckis]]' ''A Christmas Carol'' and ''[[The Adventures of Tintin: Secret of the Unicorn]]'' directed by [[Steven Spielberg]]. He also starred in the [[Mystery film|mystery]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] ''Shadows'', directed by [[John Penney]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17894 AFM '09: Carey Elwes in 'Shadows', First Hi-Res Stills]&lt;/ref&gt; Elwes portrayed Dr. Clement in the psychological thriller ''Psych 9'',&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/37390/video-interviews-psych-9-michael-biehn-cary-elwes-and-sara-foster Video Interviews: Psych 9 – Michael Biehn, Cary Elwes, and Sara Foster]&lt;/ref&gt; which was directed by [[Andrew Shortell]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36521/new-psych-9-stills-go-mad-over New Psych 9 Stills to Go Mad Over]&lt;/ref&gt; Elwes returned to the ''Saw'' franchise in ''[[Saw 3D]]'', the seventh film in the series, as [[Dr. Lawrence Gordon]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19954/|title=Cary Elwes Confirmed for 'Saw 3D', Full Synopsis and Cast|work=Bloody Disgusting|publisher=The Collective|date=25 April 2010|accessdate=25 April 2010|&lt;!--archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5pFMaRGrL|archivedate=April 25, 2010--&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt; In January 2010,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.scannain.com/movie-news/yellow-submarine-zemeckis-finds-cast Yellow Submarine – Zemeckis finds cast]&lt;/ref&gt; it was announced that Elwes had been chosen to portray [[George Harrison]] in Robert Zemeckis' 3-D performance capture re-telling of ''[[Yellow Submarine (2012 film)|Yellow Submarine]]''.

===Television===
In 1996, Elwes made his first television appearance as &quot;David Lookner&quot; on the sitcom ''[[Seinfeld]]''. In 1998, he played astronaut [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]] in the [[Golden Globe Award]]-winning [[HBO]] [[miniseries]] ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth To the Moon]].'' In 1999, he guest starred as Dr. John York in an episode of the television series ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''. He earned two [[Satellite Awards|Golden Satellite Award]] nominations for his performances in the television films ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]'' and ''[[Uprising (film)|Uprising]]''. Elwes had a recurring role in the final season (2001–2002) of ''[[The X-Files]]'' as [[FBI Assistant Director]] [[Brad Follmer]].

In 2004, he played [[serial killer]] [[Ted Bundy]] in the [[A&amp;E Network]] television film ''The Riverman'', which was based on the book ''[[The Riverman: Ted Bundy and I Hunt for the Green River Killer]]'' written by [[Robert D. Keppel]]. In 2005 Elwes played the young [[Pope John Paul II]] in the [[CBS]] telefilm ''[[Pope John Paul II (film)|Pope John Paul II]]''.

In 2007, he made a guest appearance on the ''[[Law &amp; Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' episode &quot;[[Law &amp; Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep14|Dependent]]&quot; as a [[Mafia]] lawyer. In 2009, he played the role of Pierre Despereaux, an international art thief, in the 4th season premiere of ''[[Psych]]''.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18568 Two Clips from UK Horror-Thriller 'Psych: 9']&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35164/first-two-teaser-clips-psych-9 First Two Teaser Clips ''Psych: 9'']&lt;/ref&gt; In 2010, he returned to ''[[Psych]]'', reprising his role in the second half of the 5th season.&lt;ref&gt;[http://nicegirlstv.com/2010/10/27/first-look-cary-elwes-returns-to-psych/ First Look: Cary Elwes Returns to 'Psych']&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2011, Cary Elwes was chosen as Henry Demeter or Henry Johns, CEO Themyscira Industries, founded by Diana Prince (Adrianne Palicki) in new series[[Wonder Woman]] pilot.

===Voiceovers===
Elwes' [[voice-over]] work includes the narrator in [[James Patterson]]'s audio book ''The Jester''&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news  |title=The Jester |work=ISBN 1-58621-535-3 |publisher=Hachette Audio, Abridged edition |date=1 March 2003}}&lt;/ref&gt; as well as characters in film and television animations such as ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'', ''[[Pinky and The Brain]]'', ''[[Batman Beyond]]'', and the English versions of the highly popular [[Studio Ghibli]] films ''[[Porco Rosso]]'', ''[[Whisper of the Heart (film)|Whisper of the Heart]]'' and ''[[The Cat Returns]]''. For the 2004 video game ''[[The Bard's Tale (2004)|The Bard's Tale]]'', he served as scriptwriter, improviser, and [[voice acting|voice actor]] of the main character The Bard.

===Theatre===
Elwes performed in the [[Bob Balaban]]-directed [[Off-Broadway]] dramatic stage play ''[[The Exonerated]]'' in New York during its March 18–23, 2003 week run.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

==''Saw'' settlement==
In August 2005, he filed a lawsuit against his management firm and the producers of ''[[Saw (film)|Saw]]''. He alleged that he was promised a percentage of the profits and did not receive the full amount as promised.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Saw lawsuit |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/not-everyone-happy-with-their-cut-from-saw/2005/08/20/1124435169494.html |publisher=[[theage.com.au]] |date=20 August 2005}}&lt;/ref&gt; The producers eventually [[legal settlement|settled out of court]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.fangoria.com/index.php?id=641:saw-vii-synopsis-and-cast-revealedincluding-cary-elwes&amp;option=com_content&amp;catid=1:latest-news&amp;Itemid=167 “SAW VII” SYNOPSIS AND CAST REVEALED—INCLUDING CARY ELWES!]&lt;/ref&gt; Elwes later went on to reprise his role as Dr. Lawrence Gordon in ''[[Saw 3D]]''.

