'''Chick Publications''' is an American publishing company founded and run by [[Jack T. Chick]] which produces and markets [[Fundamentalist Christianity|Protestant fundamentalist]] pamphlets, [[DVD]]s, [[Video CD|VCDs]], [[video]]s, [[book]]s, and [[poster]]s. Chick Publications' best-known products are [[Chick tract]]s, which are [[comics|comic]] [[tract (literature)|tract]]s that are available in nearly 100 languages.  Arguably all of its products promote and seek to win converts to Christian fundamentalism. While some tracts express views that are generally accepted within Christian theology, e.g. the [[Incarnation (Christianity)|Incarnation of Christ]],&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0039/0039_01.asp Charlie's Ants]'', Jack Chick, 1997.&lt;/ref&gt; other tracts have controversial views and criticisms against cultures, religions and theological concepts. The [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] labels the organization as a [[hate group]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Active U.S. Hate&quot;&gt;{{cite web
 | title=Active General Hate Groups
 | publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]
 | url=http://www.splcenter.org/node/105/activegroups
 | accessdate=2011-01-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chick Publications has its headquarters in [[Rancho Cucamonga, California|Rancho Cucamonga]],&lt;ref name=&quot;Company Profile:Chi&quot;/&gt; while it has an [[Ontario, California]] mailing address. All of Chick Publications' tracts, and several excerpts from his full-length comics, may be read without charge at the Chick website.  Many older tracts are out of print; however, Chick Publications will print a minimum 10,000 tract special order of any out-of-print series.

On the company's website they also note that &quot;Our ministry is primarily publishing the gospel tracts of Jack T. Chick, but we do occasionally publish a manuscript in book form.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;FAQ: Will Chick Pu&quot;&gt;{{cite web
| title=FAQ: Will Chick Publications publish my book?
| publisher= Chick Publications, Inc.
| date=1984-2008
| url =http://www.chick.com/information/general/chickinfo.asp#publish
| accessdate=2008-02-25}}&lt;/ref&gt; They state that if the content &quot;educates Christians in one of the areas for which we have a tract, we would love to see it&quot; and cite several examples; the online store lists nearly a dozen book categories.&lt;ref name=&quot;FAQ: Will Chick Pu&quot;/&gt;

==Overview==
The company's web site lists more than 150 comic tracts; all of them can be viewed online, but other materials can generally only be sampled.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/catalog/tractlist.asp English Chick Cartoon Tracts]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt; The site states that several hundred million tracts have been distributed worldwide, with some of them translated into almost 100 languages. However, for the majority of languages, only one tract is available: ''This Was Your Life''. This tract is unique in that, apart from the large number of languages it is published in, it also appears in six different artwork versions, depicting the major racial groups.

Like many other religious publishing organizations, Chick Publications does not distribute their tracts for free; they are normally purchased in bulk by the people handing them out.

[[Image:'love the jewish people' chick tract in restroom.jpg|thumb|left|[[Tract (literature)|Tract]] by [[Jack T. Chick]] entitled &quot;Love The Jewish People&quot; inside a [[public toilet|restroom stall]].]]

While Chick's tracts are meant to be handed out directly (for instance, he encourages Christians to give out anti-[[Halloween]] tracts along with Halloween candy&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/seasonal/halloween/default.asp?FROM=Tracttips Halloween...witnessing doesn't get any easier]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt;), they are often distributed by leaving them in places where they will be found and read (for example, public restrooms), an appealing witnessing tool for shy Christians.&lt;ref name=&quot;too-shy&quot;&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/bc/1996/witnessingideas.asp I Am Too Shy To Talk To People]&quot;, ''Battle Cry'', September/October 1996.&lt;/ref&gt; This strategy is intended to reach those who are hostile to [[evangelism|evangelists]] and unlikely to accept an offered tract, by appealing instead to their curiosity.&lt;ref name=&quot;too-shy&quot; /&gt; The Chick Publications website claims that many people have been converted by encountering Chick Publication's comic tracts.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/articles/testimonies/ What Happens To Chick Tracts AFTER You Pass Them Out?]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt;

Chick Publications also publishes conventional non-graphical books on these same topics, by authors other than Chick. Many of these are also used as sources for Chick's tracts; notable sources include [[Alberto Rivera]], [[Rebecca Brown (Christian author)|Rebecca Brown]], [[Jeff Godwin]], [[Kent Hovind]], [[Charles Chiniquy]], [[William Schnoebelen]], [[John Todd (occultist)|John Todd]], [[Avro Manhattan]], and [[Alexander Hislop]].

Copies of Chick's tracts were requested by the [[Smithsonian Institution]] to be displayed among other examples of American religious culture.&lt;ref name=OfficialBio&gt;{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jack Chick
  | publisher = Chick Publications
  | url = http://www.chick.com/information/authors/chick.asp
  | accessdate = 2008-02-20}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chick Publications, and its founder and namesake [[Jack T. Chick]], have been regularly criticized for publishing strong opinions seen as negative such as opposition to [[Freemasonry]],&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/information/religions/masonry Information on Masonry]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholicism]].&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/information/religions/catholicism Information on Roman Catholicism]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt; Many of the products also oppose [[secular]]ized holidays such as [[Halloween]] and [[Thanksgiving]],&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/1025/1025_01.asp The Missing Day]'', Jack Chick, 2005.&lt;/ref&gt; as well as several forms of entertainment such as [[role-playing game]]s and [[popular music]]. Defenders of the comics assert all his comics carry the same message: salvation through [[Jesus]].  Tracts typically follow the themes of punishment or redemption in the afterlife, or set up a confrontation between a Christian and non-Christian in order to spread a religious message. Many Chick tracts end with a non-Christian being converted to Christianity. Other endings provide a contrast between those who accept Jesus and those who reject Jesus; in some tracts, a convert receives entry to [[heaven]], while in other tracts, a non-believer is condemned to [[hell]].

Most Chick tracts end with a suggested prayer for the reader to pray to accept Christ.  In most of these tracts it is a standard [[sinner's prayer]] for [[salvation]]. In the tracts dealing with [[Catholicism]] or Islam, the prayer includes a clause to reject these religions. Included with the prayer are directions for converting to Christianity.&lt;!--Even though Catholics believe in Christ--&gt;

The graphics in Chick's tracts are often simple, but eye-catching. Some Christians consider them to be valuable [[evangelism|witnessing]] tools, due to the striking nature of the cartoons and their clear-cut messages.

== Claims ==
{{primarysources|section|date=May 2011}}
Chick's tracts and other publications make many controversial claims. Some are typical of conservative [[Protestant]] beliefs. For example, Chick claims that the theory of [[evolution]] is false,&lt;ref name=&quot;big-daddy&quot;&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0055/0055_01.asp Big Daddy?]'', Jack Chick, 2002.&lt;/ref&gt; [[homosexuality]] is sinful,&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/5003/5003_01.asp Sin City]'', Jack Chick, 2001.&lt;/ref&gt; and [[abortion]] is murder.&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/1009/1009_01.asp Who Murdered Clarice?]'', Jack Chick, 2000.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0077/0077_01.asp Baby Talk]'', Jack Chick, 1995.&lt;/ref&gt;

Others are controversial even within conservative Protestantism.  In particular, Chick's tracts make frequent reference to a vast [[Satanism|Satanic]] conspiracy controlling many of the world's organizations and institutions. Religions other than Protestantism, especially the Roman Catholic Church, are generally presented as instruments of [[Satan]]. Chick claims that the [[King James Version of the Bible]] is the [[King-James-Only Movement|only recorded word of God]], and all other editions are corrupt.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.chick.com/information/general/statementoffaith.asp Statement of Faith]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.chick.com/ask/articles/ans001.asp Why Shouldn't I just read the Greek and Hebrew?]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.chick.com/ask/articles/21centurykjv.asp What about the 21st Century King James Bible?]&lt;/ref&gt; [[Christian ecumenism]] is rejected as a ploy to corrupt true Christianity by encouraging acceptance of corrupted beliefs.

Chick's claims about Catholic, Masonic, Satanic, etc., conspiracies are based in large part on the testimony of people who claim to have been members of these groups before converting to [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]] Christianity, most prominently [[Alberto Rivera]], [[William Schnoebelen]], [[John Todd (occultist)|John Todd]], and [[Mike Warnke]]. The reliability of these sources is hotly disputed, as detailed in their individual articles.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}

=== Catholicism ===
A recurring theme in Chick's tracts is the role of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], which he presents as one of the most powerful and insidious branches of this conspiracy. According to Chick, the Catholic Church is the &quot;Great Whore&quot; referred to in the [[Book of Revelation]], and will bring about a Satanic [[New World Order (conspiracy)|New World Order]]&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0094/0094_01.asp The Last Generation]'', Jack Chick, 1992.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0030/0030_01.asp The Only Hope]'', Jack Chick, 1985.&lt;/ref&gt; before it is destroyed by [[Jesus Christ]].

Drawing on the claims of Rivera and debunked authors like [[Charles Chiniquy]], Chick claims that the Catholic Church helped to mold [[Islam]] as a tool to lure people away from Christianity,&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0062/0062_01.asp The Story Teller]'', Jack Chick, 1985.&lt;/ref&gt; that it infiltrates and attempts to destroy or corrupt all other religions and churches,&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/comics/0112/0112_allinone.asp Alberto]'' pp.17-20, Jack Chick, 1979.&lt;/ref&gt; and that it uses various means including seduction, framing, and murder to silence its critics.&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/comics/0112/0112_allinone.asp Alberto]'' pp.21-24, Jack Chick, 1979.&lt;/ref&gt; He accuses Catholicism, specifically the [[Jesuits]], of instigating the [[American Civil War]], supporting the Confederate cause and seeking to undermine the Union. When that failed, they arranged the assassination of [[Abraham Lincoln]]&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/catalog/comics/0251.asp The Big Betrayal]'', Jack Chick, 1981.&lt;/ref&gt; and created the [[Ku Klux Klan]], which happens to be anti-Catholic itself. According to Chick, the Catholic Church has also supported such ideologies as [[Nazism]] and [[Communism]] and used the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] to persecute opponents of the Catholic Church.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/bc/1989/holocaustorinquisition.asp?FROM=Catholicpage Hitler's Death Camps -- Holocaust ... or Inquisition?]&quot;, ''Battle Cry'', January/February 1989.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/books/153/153_06.asp Smokescreens]'' Chapter Six: Cover Up, Jack Chick, 1983.&lt;/ref&gt; He claims that the Catholic Church keeps &quot;the name of every Protestant church member in the world&quot; in a &quot;big computer&quot; in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] for use in future persecutions.&lt;ref&gt;''Kiss the Protestants Good-bye'', Jack Chick, 1981.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;''My name... in the Vatican?'' Jack Chick, 1996&lt;/ref&gt;
&quot;Jesuits worked closely with Marx, Engels, Trotsky, Lenin, and Stalin&quot; to create Communism, and it was &quot;believed that soon . . . Communism would rise up as the new strong daughter of the Vatican.&quot; It was Rome that instigated the [[Bolshevik Revolution]] and the murder of the [[Nicholas II of Russia|czar]]’s family.&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/comics/0114/godfathersindex.asp The Godfathers]'', Jack Chick, 1982.&lt;/ref&gt; The Communist [[liberation theology]] movement also is a Vatican plot&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0053/0053_01.asp Fat Cats]'', Jack Chick, 1989.&lt;/ref&gt; regardless of Papal condemnations, such as those from [[Pope John Paul II]], who, Chick claims, was in fact a good communist.&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/comics/0117/theprophetindex.asp The Prophet]'', Jack Chick, 1989.&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Occultism ===
Chick publications present various forms of [[occult]]ism as part of a Satanic conspiracy. Most forms of [[fantasy]] and depictions of [[magic (paranormal)|magic]], including [[Harry Potter]],&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/5012/5012_01.asp The Nervous Witch]'', Jack Chick, 2002.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Dungeons &amp; Dragons]].&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0046/0046_01.asp Dark Dungeons]'', Jack Chick, 1984.&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Halloween]] celebrations&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0011/0011_01.asp The Trick]'', Jack Chick, 1986.&lt;/ref&gt; are portrayed as an attempt to draw children into [[witchcraft]].

For example, the tract ''Boo!''&lt;ref&gt;''[http://www.chick.com/reading/tracts/0058/0058_01.asp Boo!]'', Jack Chick, 1991.&lt;/ref&gt; is set on Halloween, Satan's supposed birthday. Satan kills people while dressed as a [[chainsaw]]-wielding maniac, clad in black and wearing a [[Jack-o'-lantern]] on his head. In the tract, Chick states that the [[Druids]] of the British Isles would take victims for their [[human sacrifice]]s by force on October 31 and leave a Jack-o'-lantern in exchange. In reality, [[Squash (plant)|squash]]es or [[pumpkins]] would not have been accessible to the Druids, since squashes came from the Americas and were not brought to the British Isles until nearly a thousand years after the time of the Druids.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.aces.uiuc.edu/news/stories/news3326.html Univ of Ill. Extension] retrieved April 30, 2008&lt;/ref&gt;  Also, the Druids in this instance are seen holding an [[ankh]], which is actually an Ancient Egyptian symbol.

Many of the tracts also mention that [[Holy Communion]] is an Egyptian tradition, and portray the Egyptian people as worshiping wafers of unleavened bread as the god [[Osiris]], who is described as the sun.  In reality, Osiris was never a solar deity, but rather associated with fertility, agriculture, and death.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}

==Criticism==
{{Original research|date=June 2009}}
Chick's critics (such as talkorigins.org, Hindu American Foundation, Catholic Answers, etc.) accuse him of misrepresentation &amp;mdash; for instance, the online version of Chick's tract ''Big Daddy'' mainly uses Kent Hovind as a reference &lt;ref name=&quot;big-daddy&quot; /&gt; despite the fact that Kent Hovind has no degrees from an accredited institution in the relevant fields, the thesis referred to is of very poor quality, and his claims are at odds with the published statements of experts in the field &lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last =Vickers
  | first = Brett
  | title = Some Questionable Creationist Credentials
  | year = 1998
  | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/credentials.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last =Bartelt, Ph.D.
  | first = Foley
  | title = The Dissertation Kent Hovind Doesn't Want You to Read
  | year = 2001
  | url = http://home.austarnet.com.au/stear/bartelt_dissertation_on_hovind_thesis.htm
   | accessdate = June 24, 2009 (archive) |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070718063636/http://home.austarnet.com.au/stear/bartelt_dissertation_on_hovind_thesis.htm |archivedate = 2007-07-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last =Foley
  | first = Jim
  | title = Fossil Hominids: Big Daddy?
  | publisher = talkorigins.org
  | date = August 31, 2001
  | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/bigdaddy.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;fowler&quot;&gt;{{cite book
  | last = Fowler
  | first = Robert B.
  | title = The World of Jack T. Chick
  | year = 2001
  | publisher = Last Gasp
  | page= 2-10
  | ISBN = 0867195126}}&lt;/ref&gt; Worse, Hovind's referenced claim in ''Big Daddy'', &quot;It has never been against the law to teach the Bible or creation in public schools,&quot; is both misleading and false.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last =Spinney
  | first = Jacob
  | title = A Close Look at Dr. Hovind's List of Young-Earth Arguments and Other Claims
  | publisher = Skeptic Report
  | date = November, 2004
  | url = http://www.skepticreport.com/creationism/hovind.htm
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Matson
  | first = Dave E.
  | title = How Good Are Those Young-Earth Arguments?  A Close Look at Dr. Hovind's List of Young-Earth Arguments and Other Claims
  | publisher = talkorigins.org
  | year = 1994
  | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/hovind/howgood.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; (&quot;the U. S. Supreme Court case of [[Edwards v. Aguillard]] found that teaching Creationism alongside Evolution in the classroom was unconstitutional, violating the establishment clause.&quot;)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Matson
  | first = Dave E.
  | title = How Good Are Those Young-Earth Arguments?  A Close Look at Dr. Hovind's List of Young-Earth Arguments and Other Claims Miscellaneous Topics
  | publisher = talkorigins.org
  | year = 1994
  | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/hovind/howgood-misc.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;  In fact, the examples in the tract are either distortions, misrepresentations, or just made up strawmen to the point that it is stated that presenting Cro-magnon as something separate from ''Homo sapian'' is called &quot;deceptive and misleading.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  | last = Prothero, 
  | first = Donald R. 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Carl Dennis Buell
  | title = Evolution: what the fossils say and why it matters
  | publisher = Columbia University Press
  | year = 2007
  | pages = 334–335
  | isbn = 0231139624}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Michael Ian Borer, a sociology professor of Furman University at the time, showed in a 2007 American Sociological Association presentation&lt;ref&gt;Borer, Michael. (2007) &quot;Drawing Religious Battle Lines: The “Culture Wars Work” of Jack Chick’s Anti-Catholic Cartoons&quot;[http://www.allacademic.com/meta/p181814_index.html &quot;Drawing Religious Battle Lines: The “Culture Wars Work” of Jack Chick’s Anti-Catholic Cartoons&quot;] Paper presented at the annual meeting of the American Sociological Association, New York, New York City, Aug 11, 2007&lt;/ref&gt; and in a peer reviewed article the next year in ''Religion and American Culture''&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation
  | last = Borer 
  | first = Michael Ian
  | author-link = 
  | last2 = Murphree
  | first2 = Adam 
  | author2-link = 
  | title = Framing Catholicism: Jack Chick's Anti-Catholic Cartoons and the Flexible Boundaries of the Culture Wars
  | journal = Religion and American Culture
  | volume = 18
  | issue = 1
  | pages = 95–112
  | date = 
  | year = 2008
  | month = Winter
  | url = 
  | archiveurl =
  | archivedate =
  | doi = 
  | id = }}&lt;/ref&gt; Chick's strong anti-Catholic themes.

Catholic Answers web published a response to the claims of Chick Publications against Roman Catholics and a criticism of Chick Tracts in general called  The Nightmare World of Jack T. Chick&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.catholic.com/library/sr_chick_tracts.asp The Nightmare World of Jack T. Chick]&lt;/ref&gt; detailing the inaccuracies, factual errors, and the &quot;typical tactic in Chick tracts is to portray Catholics as being unpleasant or revolting in various ways&quot;.

The [[Hindu American Foundation]] put out electronic PDF paper called Hyperlink to Hinduphobia: Online Hatred, Extremism and Bigotry Against Hindus&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.hinduamericanfoundation.org/pdf/hate_report_2007.pdf Hyperlink to Hinduphobia: Online Hatred, Extremism and Bigotry Against Hindus]&lt;/ref&gt; which contains a section on Chick's site that ends with the statement &quot;Chick Publications promotes hatred not just against Hindus, but also towards Muslims, Catholics, and others as is evidenced by the following titles of their tracts: “Last Rites – When this Catholic dies, he learns that his church couldn't save him”; “The Little Bride – Protect children against being recruited as Muslims. Li'l Susy explains that only Jesus can save them”; and “Allah Had No Son – The Allah of Islam is not the God of creation”&quot;

Another common criticism is that Chick portrays a world full of paranoia and conspiracy where nothing is what it seems and nearly everything is a Satanic plot&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | author-link = 
  | last2 = 
  | first2 = 
  | author2-link = 
  | title = The Nightmare World of Jack T. Chick
  | date = 
  | year = 
  | url = http://www.catholic.com/library/sr_chick_tracts.asp
  | accessdate = July 31, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Hodapp, 2008 105&quot;&gt;{{Citation
  | last = Hodapp, 
  | first = Christopher 
  | author-link = 
  | last2 = Von Kannon
  | first2 = Alice
  | author2-link = 
  | title = Conspiracy Theories &amp; Secret Societies For Dummies
   | publisher = For Dummies
  | year = 2008
  | page = 105 
   | isbn = 0470184086}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation
  | last = Camp
  | first = Gregory S. 
    | title = Selling fear: conspiracy theories and end-times paranoia
   | publisher = Baker Pub Group
  | year = 1997
  | page = 189 
   | isbn = 0801057213}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Chick's claims about Catholic, Masonic, Satanic, etc., conspiracies are based in large part on the testimony of people who claim to have been members of these groups before converting to [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]] Christianity, most prominently Rivera and Schnoebelen. Many of Chick's critics consider these sources to be frauds or fantasists.&lt;ref name=&quot;fowler&quot; /&gt; One such case was &quot;The Prophet&quot;&lt;ref name=Prophet&gt;{{cite book
  | last = Chick
  | first = Jack
  | title = The Prophet
  | publisher = Chick Publications
  | year = 1988
  | url = http://www.chick.com/reading/comics/0117/theprophetindex.asp}}&lt;/ref&gt; where the fantastic tale related by [[Alberto Rivera]] turned out to have no basis in reality.&lt;ref name=&quot;Hodapp, 2008 105&quot;/&gt; Nevertheless, many Chick supporters believe their claims to be legitimate.

He has also changed the content of other tracts such as ''The Last Generation'' and his book ''The Next Step'' to reflect his increasingly anti-Catholic beliefs{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}, and the content of ''That Crazy Guy!'' was changed after the rise of the [[AIDS]] crisis (the tract was originally about [[herpes]]).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Monsterwax
  | title = Jack T. Chick's Museum of Fine Art REVIEW WING
  | year = 2000
  | url = http://www.monsterwax.com/chickreviews.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Also, the ending to ''The Poor Little Witch'' (in which a little girl is murdered by Satanists after forsaking Occultism and converting to Fundamentalist Christianity) was changed because the urban myth, which states that &quot;every year in the U.S. at least 40,000 people... are murdered in witchcraft ceremonies&quot; (about twice the entire reported homicide rate for the USA), turned out to be false and was removed from the tract.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/homicide/tables/totalstab.htm Homicide victimization, 1950-2005], [[United States Bureau of Justice Statistics]], [[United States Department of Justice]], July 11, 2007&lt;/ref&gt;  Chick Publications depict [[Paganism]] and [[Neo-Paganism]] as a form of [[Satanism]], a position Neo-Pagans and other observers strongly dispute.

One claim that used to pop up frequently in Chick's publications was that the Soviet Union would invade [[Israel]] under orders of the Pope, with [[East Germany]] aiding it. Tracts that used to contain this claim (like &quot;Escape&quot;) had it removed in later revisions. {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} It can still be seen on Page 33 of &quot;The Godfathers.&quot;

The Chick Publications website is [[Censorship in Singapore|blocked in Singapore]].&lt;ref&gt;http://www.trevvy.com/scoops/article.php?a_id=348&lt;/ref&gt; In December 2008, a Singaporean couple was charged with [[sedition]] for distributing the Chick tracts ''The Little Bride'' and ''Who Is Allah?'', said to &quot;to promote feelings of ill-will and hostility between Christians and Muslims in Singapore&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Chong
  | first = Elena
  | title = Couple on sedition trial
  | publisher = Straits Times
  | date = December 4, 2008
  | url = http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_310229.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Chong
  | first = Elena
  | title = No ill will intended
  | publisher = Aquarian Tabernacle Church
  | date = December 6, 2008
  | url = http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_310849.html
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Some of the criticism of Chick tracts has taken the form of parody tracts pointing out all the errors (logical and factual) in the originals. ''Big Daddy'' was satirized by ''Who's Your Daddy?'',&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.facts4u.com/OffSite_Stored_Pages/wyd_files/wyd.htm ''Who's Your Daddy?'']&lt;/ref&gt; ''Somebody Loves You'' was satirized by ''Somebody Loves You?'',&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.luciferianliberationfront.org/sly.html ''Somebody Loves You?'']&lt;/ref&gt; and ''Gun Slinger'' was satirized by  ''The Good, The Bad, and the Fundy''.&lt;ref&gt;The Jack T. Chick Parody Archive (defunct as of March 27 2011)&lt;/ref&gt;  At least one satire website has claimed improper copyright claims by Chick Publications&lt;ref&gt;The Jack T. Chick Parody Archive (defunct as of March 27 2011)&lt;/ref&gt; to remove parody tracts despite the fact parodies and satires are exempt from copyright law per ''[[Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.]]'', ''[[Leibovitz v. Paramount Pictures Corp.]]'', and ''[[Suntrust v. Houghton Mifflin]]''.

==Defense==
Many [[fundamentalist]] Protestants, both past and present, agree with at least some of Chick Publications' more controversial claims.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} Some reject Chick's Roman Catholic conspiracy theories but accept other claims promoted in his tracts (such as his view that a person must be saved so as to avoid [[eternal damnation]] in Hell), and so offer qualified agreement with Chick's beliefs.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} Some anti-[[cult]] organizations view Chick's website and publications as a valuable source of material on groups they see as cults.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.missionresources.com/cult.html Information on Cults Resource Directory]&quot;, World Christian Resource Directory.&lt;/ref&gt;

Jack Chick claims that [[cartoon]]s are a more effective medium for witnessing than conventional text based tracts. Some of the characteristics often seen as failings of his tracts - for instance, their simplistic messages - can also be viewed as strengths, making them more appealing to readers who are unsympathetic to more conventional forms of evangelism. Some tracts go further, and use only words aimed at children, or tell their stories without words. Recently people in cartoons have been colored in to appeal more to black people.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.chick.com/newseries.asp?wpc=newseries.asp&amp;wpp=a New Series from Chick Publications]&quot;, Chick Publications.&lt;/ref&gt;

Chick's more controversial claims are usually accompanied by supporting references to the [[Bible]] (always quoting the King James Version), other books (often also published by Chick), and historical facts; debate commonly focuses on the reliability of these sources and of Chick's representation of them.

== Cultural influence ==
Jack T. Chick's tracts have had an unintentional influence on pop culture. The Chick Tract Club was established for collectors of Chick's works. A website for parodies of his works (The Jack T. Chick Parody Archive) was on line. Kurt Kuersteiner, the author of ''The Unofficial Guide to the Art of Jack T. Chick'', has produced a [[Documentary film|documentary]] on Jack Chick and his works entitled ''God's Cartoonist: The Comic Crusade of Jack Chick''. Comedian [[David Cross]] (a self-professed [[atheist]] &lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | title = David_Cross
  | publisher = celebrity atheist list
  | url =http://www.celebatheists.com/index.php?title=David_Cross
  | accessdate = June 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;) released a DVD of his comedy works entitled ''[[Let America Laugh]]'' with the chapters titled after Chick tracts (''This Was Your Life'', ''Who Cares?'', ''Is There Another Christ?'', ''Gomez Is Coming'', etc.).

